        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "The cost to use nvim_win_call can add up if it's used in hot paths. When I tested, it was actually faster to run `nvim_get_current_win()` first to see if it could be avoided.\n\n> > This still uses `vim.fn`. I think it would be better to have a `vim.api` that can do this.\n> \n> `vim.fn` interop (marshalling to/from `typval_T`) has about the same cost as `vim.api` (marshalling to/from `Object`)\n> \n> but, can you confirm if the PR I linked above covers your use-case?\n\nWhere the cost of the eval functions seems to add up is variety of possibilities in the data they can return. Using `line()` to get a piece of data is slower than the api alternatives where they are available. Or in the case of `getwininfo()`, not everything it returns is needed in every case.\n\nIf you're doing some kind of pre-defined or bulk process, you can structure context changes or save the results of eval calls (such as sticking all fold checks in a window inside one context switch, or passing topline and botline around). But this makes it difficult to break anything that depends on context switching or eval functions into composable pieces.",
            "created_at": "2026-05-07T13:09:24Z",
            "html_url": "https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/39636#issuecomment-4397384350",
            "id": 4397384350,
            "issue_url": "https://api.github.com/repos/neovim/neovim/issues/39636",
